│ tries to vectorize them.\n2.  **Operand Bundling:** It works its way up the use-def     │
│ chain, bundling operands. It successfully bundles the stored values: `[%add5, %add9,    │
│ %add12, 0]`.\n3.  **Problematic Scheduling Attempt:** It then tries to bundle the       │
│ operands of *that* group: `[%call, %add7, %add4, 0]`. The log notes: `reset schedule    │
│ because %call ... was already scheduled`. This is a critical clue. The scheduler is     │
│ re-evaluating an instruction it has already processed, which often leads to             │
│ inconsistent state. It fails to schedule this bundle.\n4.  **Second Problematic         │
│ Attempt:** The vectorizer backtracks and tries another combination for the operands of  │
│ the stored values: `[%mul1, %add4, %add11, 0]`. Again, the log shows: `reset schedule   │
│ because %mul1 ... was already scheduled`.\n5.  **The Crash:** It proceeds to try        │
│ scheduling `[<Copyable> %mul1, %add4, %add11]`. It updates dependencies for `%mul1`     │
│ (which is a copy) and then for `%add11`. The crash occurs immediately after, when       │
│ trying to update the dependencies of a user of `%add11`.\n\nThe key takeaway is the     │
│ repeated \"reset schedule because ... was already scheduled\" message. This happens     │
│ when `buildTreeRec` encounters an instruction that is already part of another           │
│ `TreeEntry`. In this specific case, the IR has multiple uses of the same values (e.g.,  │
│ `%add` is used to compute both `%add4` and `%add11`), which complicates the             │
│ tree-building logic. The scheduler is getting confused by the DAG structure, leading it │
│ to try to schedule the same nodes multiple times in a way that corrupts its internal    │
│ dependency tracking state.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies in the  │
│ interaction between the bottom-up tree building (`buildTreeRec`) and the instruction    │
│ scheduler (`BlockScheduling`). When `buildTreeRec` encounters an instruction that's     │
│ already been included in the SLP tree (as part of another bundle), it correctly         │
│ identifies this and attempts to create a \"copy\" of the node for scheduling            │
│ purposes.\n\nHowever, the logic for handling these copied nodes during the scheduling   │
│ feasibility check (`tryScheduleBundle`) is flawed. When the scheduler processes a       │
│ bundle containing a copied instruction, it calls `resetSchedule()` to clear its         │
│ internal state. The problem is that this reset is incomplete. It clears the dependency  │
│ counts but does not re-initialize the `ScheduleData` for all the instructions in the    │
│ current scheduling region.\n\nIn our case, `%add` is used by both `%add4` and `%add11`. │
│ The vectorizer processes `%add4` first. Later, when it processes `%add11`, it sees that │
│ `%add` is already in the tree. When it tries to schedule the bundle containing          │
│ `%add11`, it triggers the `resetSchedule()` path. Because the `ScheduleData` for the    │
│ users of the bundle (like `%add12`) is not properly re-initialized after the reset, its │
│ `Dependencies` count remains at an invalid state (`-1`). When the scheduler later tries │
│ to update the dependencies by calling `incrementUnscheduledDeps`, the                   │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` assertion correctly fails.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit             │
│ Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to ensure that when we `resetSchedule()` due to finding an       │
│ already-scheduled instruction (a \"copy\"), we properly re-initialize the dependency    │
│ data for all entities in the current scheduling region. This is done by iterating over  │
│ the `ScheduleRegion` and calling `initScheduleData` for each entity.\n\nI will replace  │
│ the existing `if (IsCopy)` block with a corrected version.\n\n**File**:                 │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp`\n**Lines**: 20792-20794\n**Original   │
│ Code**:\n```cpp\n    if (IsCopy) {\n      resetSchedule();\n    }\n```\n\n**Proposed    │
│ Code**:\n```cpp\n    if (IsCopy) {\n      resetSchedule();\n      for (ScheduleEntity   │
│ *SE : ScheduleRegion)\n        initScheduleData(SE, ScheduleRegion, EdgeInfo);\n        │
│ }\n```\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe proposed change ensures that whenever the scheduler  │
│ has to reset its state due to encountering an instruction that is already part of the   │
│ SLP-tree, it correctly re-initializes the dependency metadata for all instructions in   │
│ the current scheduling attempt. This prevents the scheduler from trying to update       │
│ dependency counts on uninitialized data structures, thus fixing the assertion failure.  │
│ With this patch, the SLP vectorizer will be able to correctly analyze the complex DAG   │
│ in the reproducer, avoid the crash, and proceed with vectorization if it deems it       │
│ profitable."                                                                            │
│ }                                                                                       │
